Grokking Git: A Fantasy Story

<p>Git is a big part of a lot of tech worker’s every day lives, but it can be confusing to use. There’s good news and bad news.</p> <p>The bad news is, Git is complex; there’s a lot of confusing commands.</p> <p>The good news is, that the way Git is designed under the hood makes more sense than its interface.</p> <p>We’re not going to learn any command incantations, and we’re not going to learn recipes on how to do specific things. Each picture you take grows a knot on the branch, saving the work for the art show pristinely on the trunk.</p> <hr> <p>These magic photo tree branches are like Git branches. Instead of being limited to a linear work stream, you can have as many branches in different states and histories as you like. This is makes work much more efficient, especially when collaborating with others.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch --create branch-name <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># or, use -c instead of --create</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;merging&#34;>Merging</h2> <p>Half way through work on your Sewer Gala scene, you have an idea for another scene with critters gardening. You want to capture those ideas while they’re fresh; you create a new branch from the tree trunk.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch main </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch --create garden-branch </span></span></code></pre></div><p>You get so carried away sculpting the garden and its inhabitants, you almost finish the scene before you realize how much time has passed!</p> <p>Switching back to your sewer branch, you continue your hot streak and almost finish <em>that</em> one before the day of your art show.</p> <p>You can see patrons winding up the mountain road to your cottage. You switch back to the trunk. Now, only the work there appears on your work bench, without anything from the sewer or garden. Then, you spend the rest of the time before people arrive dusting.</p> <p>Your show is a success! The visitors all like your work, except for the critic Harold Martimus, but he doesn’t like puppies, so his judgment is suspect.</p> <p>The next day, you finish both the sewer and the garden scenes. Great! Yet, now you have a problem.</p> <p>You have three separate branches, each with different work. back into its trunk, and stare in awe as the branches bend and then merge with the tree trunk. Now the tree’s trunk has all your branch knots!</p> <hr> <p>The tree branches growing in are like Git merges. The concept is pretty simple; take those changes over there, and combine them with these changes over here.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch main </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git merge sewer-gala-branch </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git merge garden-branch </span></span></code></pre></div><p>Git keeps track of <em>how</em> the branches came apart, and then back together, like the tree’s bending branches. This is important for Git to keep things organized internally, but it&rsquo;s also useful for seeing how your work has evolved.</p> <p>Running Git log with the graph option is like going outside and looking at how your tree has grown.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git log --graph </span></span></code></pre></div><p>Sometimes, a merge will not create a bending history. In our example, this would happen if our trunk, aka main branch, didn’t change at all since we made our changes in <code>sewer-gala-branch</code>. Since the <code>sewer-gala-branch</code> contains every commit the <code>main</code> branch does, and every commit in the <code>sewer-gala-branch</code> happened after the commits in the <code>main</code> branch, the newly merged commits go right on top of the others in the <code>main</code> branch, without a bending branch visual. This is called a fast forward merge, and happens automatically unless you tell Git not to.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git merge sewer-gala --no-ff <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># always bend branches</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;tags--hashes&#34;>Tags &amp; Hashes</h2> <p>As you&rsquo;re working, you happen to stare closely at a knot on the tree, aka a commit. You are surprised to see a long series of letters and numbers.</p> <p>“Oh, that’s a hash!” Hollers mail carrier Julia, walking up your drive.</p> <p>&ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t say anything out loud.&rdquo; You say, scratching your head. &ldquo;How did you know what I was thinking?&rdquo;</p> <p>“Every knot has a hash,” Julia says, ignoring your question. “The tree creates them from a combination of what you changed and the message you wrote. It uniquely identifies each knot. You can use hashes any time you want to refer to a knot.”</p> <p>“That’s pretty cool,” you say, “and let me guess, the hashes are created through magic.”</p> <p>“Nope!” Julia hoots, “It’s math.”</p> <p>You frown. “How does the math work?”</p> <p>Julia’s eyes dart back and forth. “Uhh…magic?”</p> <p>“Wait, but you said…”</p> <p>But mail carrier Julia is gone.</p> <p>You start thinking about the hashes, and while it is nice that every knot has one you can use, it would be even nicer to be able to give it an easier to remember name.</p> <p>You’ve had to jump back to the knot of your art show a few times now, and it would be nice to be able to mark seminal moments like that for quick reference.</p> <p>You etch a name on the knot from your art show with your pen knife.</p> <p><svg xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#34; role=&#34;img&#34; aria-label=&#34;A hand drawn image of the tree with merged branches from before, only now an etched note is tied to a knot. name instead of the hash.</p> <hr> <p>Every commit has a cryptographic hash to uniquely identify it. Git uses this to keep track of each commit, and for compression. You can use this hash any time you want to reference a commit.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git show 7afd021 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># display commit information</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch --detach 7afd021 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># switch to commit</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><p>Etching a name into a knot, while a bad idea with real trees, is a good idea in Git. It is like Git tags. You use them to name a commit. Unlike branches, which by nature change over time as commits are added, a tag always points to the commit it’s assigned to.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git tag v1 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># tag the current commit with the name &#34;v1&#34;</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git tag 7afd021 v1 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># tag commit hash 7afd021 with the name &#34;v1&#34;</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch --detach v1 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># switch current commit using the tag</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><p>A tag&rsquo;s immutable nature makes them popular for marking releases.</p> <h2 id=&#34;detached-head&#34;>Detached head</h2> <p>Your friend Laird pays you a visit. is like Git&rsquo;s detached head state. Detached head sounds scary, given how fatal that is for humans. However, we&rsquo;re dealing with Git, and Git is completely inhumane, so it&rsquo;s fine.</p> <p>Anytime you check out a commit that isn&rsquo;t at the tip of a branch, including the main branch, you are in detached head state. Like the magical tree, Git only adds new commits to the tip of a branch. If you make a commit when you&rsquo;re not checked out at the tip of a branch, you can only merge it if you create a new branch.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch --detach HEAD~4 <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># Go back 4 commits</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span><span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># make some changes</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git add . <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># &#34;.&#34; means everything in the current folder</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git commit --message <span style=&#34;color:#e6db74&#34;>&#34;My detached change&#34;</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git switch main </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git branch my-branch-name <span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;>[</span>commit-hash<span style=&#34;color:#f92672&#34;>]</span> <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># switching branches will show help that gives the commit hash</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git merge my-branch-name </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;repositories&#34;>Repositories</h2> <p>The deadline for your mysterious donor looms. and tree system were <em>designed</em> for collaboration,” she says, through bites of her Huckleberry jam sandwich.</p> <p>“You can connect to anyone who has the same magical system,” Julia says. “You can connect to them directly, but that&rsquo;s hard for everyone to follow, and setup. It&rsquo;s easier if everyone points to the same central hub.”</p> <p>She points at the sky. “See that big cloud over there? The one that looks a bit like a cat, and a bit like an octopus? That’s a magical cloud. We can send it your work, and others far away can receive it.”</p> <p>Julia removes a seed from a pouch, and flings it into the sky. It shoots straight into the cloud, disappearing with a puff. She points at the spot it vanished, handing you a telescope. You peer through it.</p> <p>“See that?” She says. “That seed is nestled in the cloud. It’s the same type of seed that grew the magic tree planted in your yard. When we send the cloud your work, that seed up there will grow exactly the way your tree down here did.”</p> <hr> <p>The magical cloud is like a Git service provider, such as Github or Drupal.org. A Git service provider acts as a central place for many people to access the same code and change history. You can collaborate with others without one, but it&rsquo;s annoying and technically challenging.</p> <p>The seed of the tree in the cloud is like setting up an empty repository in a Git service provider. Every Git project, wherever it is, needs this basic structure. That&rsquo;s because a Git repository is basically the same anywhere it exists, which allows it to be hosted anywhere. cloud.”</p> <p>You scratch your head. “Uhh, why?”</p> <p>Julia rolls her eyes. “You’ll see. Just say the magic words.”</p> <p>You sigh, say the magic words, and nothing happens. You wait. Still nothing. “Is something supposed to happen?” You ask. Mail carrier Julia is beaming.</p> <p>“It already did! You’re connected.”</p> <p>“Oh,” you reply, “so is my work in the cloud?”</p> <p>“No, silly goose, you just made the connection. We’ll get your work in the cloud in a moment.”</p> <hr> <p>Connecting the chimney to the cloud is like adding a Git remote. A remote is the location of your project in another place, like a Git cloud provider, a sever somewhere, or even another folder on your computer. As long as it has the basic Git structure, you can add it as a remote.</p> <p>It may seem like extra busy work, but this is part of Git&rsquo;s flexibility and decentralization. It allows any instance of a Git repository to connect to any other versions of the project else where. You can even connect to <em>different</em> projects, although that&rsquo;s beyond the scope of this article.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git remote add origin git@github.com:you/critters.git <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># Add a remote</span> </span></span><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git remote --verbose <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># See which remotes are set up; or, instead of --verbose use -v</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><p>If you clone a repository from a Git service like Github, the remote will automatically be set up for you.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git clone git@github.com:you/critters.git </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;pushing&#34;>Pushing</h2> <p>“We did a bunch of stuff, but I just want to collaborate with other artists.” You say, thinking about your deadline.</p> <p>“Don’t have a cow,” mail carrier Julia says. “Switch your workbench to the branch you want to send, and say the magic words.”</p> <p>You say the magic words to change to your main branch, then, say some more magic words to send your changes.</p> <p>As soon as the phrase has left your lips, a ghostly image of your magic tree’s trunk separates from the tree itself, wafts into the living room, then zooms up the chimney. You race outside to watch it streak up into the cloud, vanishing in a flash of light. Why not send that one up? You switch to that branch, say the magic words, and the ghost images shoot up the chimney and into the cloud. With your telescope, you can see that both branches live side-by-side in the cloud, like folders on your computer.</p> <p>You tell your artist friends; they have been using this magic system for years! They can now receive your changes in the cloud and start their own work.</p> <hr> <p>Sending ghostly images up through a chimney is…insane, but it is also a bit like pushing with Git. A git push sends your currently checked out branch to a remote. If you have more than one remote, you can choose which one to send to.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git push </span></span></code></pre></div><p>If you have more than one remote configured, you’ll need to say the name of the remote you want to use.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git push upstream </span></span></code></pre></div><p>A Git push recreates everything about your current branch at the remote location: all the files, the history of commits, their messages, author data. Everything.</p> <p>The one exception is tags, which are not pushed by default. If you’ve made a tag on your computer, and would like to push it to your remote, you’ll need to add the <code>--tags</code> option.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git push --tags </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;pulling&#34;>Pulling</h2> <p>Your artist friends work hard on the fireworks and the bridge, and pretty soon, they’re ready for you to see it. This time, you grilled mail carrier Julia on how to do this before she disappeared. You’re ready. Your artist friend who built the bridge added their changes to your main branch in the cloud, which was copied directly from the magic tree in your yard.</p> <p>Famously, clouds don’t talk to chimneys. That is, unless you ask them to. <p>While you’re dancing with joy, your bridge artist friend lets you know that there’s another knot waiting for you in the cloud—they improved the bridge’s structural integrity. You remember something Julia said about a shortcut. Instead of getting the knowledge about the changes in the cloud and merging the branch from the cloud with the one in your home in separate steps, you say magic words that combine the two.</p> <p>&ldquo;Git pull!&rdquo; You shout. Boom, you’ve got the improved bridge, <em>and</em> you’ve saved your voice!</p> <hr> <p>Git won’t do anything unless you ask it to. That includes updating Git’s knowledge of what exists up on the remote.</p> <p>Running Git fetch will update Git’s understanding of what has happened in the cloud since it last connected, and store that data locally, but won’t change anything else.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git fetch </span></span></code></pre></div><p>A merge is flexible. You can merge two branches you made on your computer together, or you can merge a branch you grabbed from the cloud with one on your computer.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git merge origin/main <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># here, you always need to say the remote name</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><p>Git pull combines the fetch and merge step for the current branch.</p> <div class=&#34;highlight&#34;><pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;><code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;><span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;><span>git pull <span style=&#34;color:#75715e&#34;># Like git fetch &amp;&amp; git merge origin/[branch-name]</span> </span></span></code></pre></div><h2 id=&#34;pull-requests&#34;>Pull Requests</h2> <p>Your other artist friend who worked on the fireworks is ready for you to look at their work. However, their changes are more involved. They needed to affix stems to hold up the fireworks onto streets and buildings you sculpted, and they’d like to make sure everything is okay before you merge.</p> <p>You get a letter detailing everything they changed, with where to look in the cloud to see their branch in detail. When you look through your telescope, you see cloudy images of what <em>would</em> happen <em>if</em> you merged the branch!</p> <p><svg xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#34; aria-label=&#34;A hand drawn image of a letter.
